"# Chapter 7 — The module fold — one program, many modules

Big programs in Motoi are not built by growing one file to a thousand lines. They are built by combining many small modules that each hold a few verbs. This shape has a name: the **module fold**.

Understanding the module fold is the difference between writing Motoi and writing something-that-looks-like-Motoi-but-collapses-under-its-own-weight.

## 7.1 What the fold looks like

A program that uses three modules — `graphics`, `sound`, `input` — folds them into one game:

```scheme
(import graphics :as g)
(import sound :as s)
(import input :as i)

(define (frame)
  (let ((keys (i/read-keys)))
    (when (i/key-down? keys 'space)
      (s/play 'jump))
    (g/clear)
    (g/draw-sprite 'player 100 100))
  (g/present))

(define (main)
  (i/init)
  (g/init)
  (s/init)
  (forever frame))

(main)
```

The program is short. Almost everything it does is delegated to a module. `graphics` handles drawing. `sound` handles playback. `input` handles keys. The program's job is to *fold* them together — to say *here is the sequence of things to call each frame*.

## 7.2 Why fold works

Because each module has one job, each module is small enough to understand. `graphics` does not need to know about sound. `sound` does not need to know about input. The program is the only thing that knows about all three, and its knowledge is thin — it calls verbs in a particular order.

When something goes wrong, you isolate it. Sound is silent? Look at `sound` alone. Input feels laggy? Look at `input` alone. Sprite is invisible? Look at `graphics` alone. You do not have to hold the whole program in your head.

## 7.3 The fold vs the pile

The opposite of the fold is the pile: one program with a thousand verbs of its own, no modules, everything in one file. Piles are easier to write on day one and harder to work with on every day after.

The choice between fold and pile is often not a deliberate one — programs drift toward the pile because the pile is what you get by default when you keep adding verbs without pausing to ask *should this be a module?*

The habit to build: whenever you find yourself writing a helper that has nothing to do with the current program's specific purpose, ask whether it belongs in a module. If it does, cut it. Even a two-verb module is worth the extraction, because a two-verb module can be reused later without any refactoring.

## 7.4 A fold with initialization

Modules often need to be initialized — file handles opened, tables precomputed, connections established. The fold handles this explicitly:

```scheme
(import graphics :as g)
(import sound :as s)
(import input :as i)

(define (main)
  (i/init)
  (g/init :width 800 :height 600)
  (s/init :channels 8)
  (forever frame))
```

`i/init`, `g/init`, `s/init` are the modules' init verbs. The program calls them in the right order. If order matters — say, sound has to init before graphics because graphics wants to hear the sound engine's sample rate — the fold makes that dependency visible.

Init order is one of the places where a pile hides bugs. When everything is in one file, init order is implicit; when everything is in modules, init order is a sequence the fold spells out.

## 7.5 A fold with teardown

Symmetrically, modules often need cleanup — files to close, connections to drop, memory to free. The fold handles teardown too:

```scheme
(define (main)
  (i/init)
  (g/init)
  (s/init)
  (dynamic-wind
    (lambda () #f)
    (lambda () (forever frame))
    (lambda ()
      (s/shutdown)
      (g/shutdown)
      (i/shutdown))))
```

The teardown runs in reverse init order. That is a common pattern — you tear down in the opposite order you brought up.

## 7.6 Sharing state across modules

Modules do not share state by default. If `graphics` needs to know the current window size and `input` needs to know it too, the two modules do not share a variable — one of them owns the window and the other asks for it.

The program acts as the mediator:

```scheme
(import graphics :as g)
(import input :as i)

(define (main)
  (g/init :width 800 :height 600)
  (i/set-window! (g/current-window)))
```

`graphics` owns the window. `input` receives a reference to it. This is verbose compared to a shared global, and it is deliberately verbose. The verbosity makes the dependency visible. If you later want to swap in a different graphics module, you know exactly what `input` needs from it — the current window.

## 7.7 The fold is a spec

The imports and init sequence at the top of a program are, in a real sense, a specification of what the program is made of. Read the top ten lines and you know the shape.

This is one of the reasons the module fold matters more than it looks like it should: it makes programs self-documenting. Not with comments — with structure. A reader who has never seen your program can look at the top and know *this is a game that draws sprites, plays sounds, and reads keys*. That is a lot to know from ten lines.

## 7.8 Try it

Take a small program you have written that has grown past a few hundred lines. Look for verbs that could be their own module — anything general-purpose, anything that has nothing to do with the program's specific job. Extract one into a module. Import it back. Verify the program still works.

Do it again with a second candidate. Notice how the main file starts to look like a fold — imports at the top, small `main` at the bottom, most of the work delegated.

Chapter 8 covers cross-cart modules — how modules in Curator can span multiple carts without belonging to any one. Turn the page.")
